To achieve the desired functionality in a sap.m.Tree control with multi-selection enabled, you can use the following example code:

```javascript
// Assuming you have a sap.m.Tree control with id "myTree" defined in your XML view or created programmatically

var tree = sap.ui.getCore().byId("myTree");

// Assuming you have an event handler function for the selection change event of the sap.m.Tree control
function onSelectionChange(event) {
  var selectedItems = event.getParameter("selectedItems");

  // Iterate through the selected items
  selectedItems.forEach(function(selectedItem) {
    var itemPath = selectedItem.getBindingContext().getPath();

    // Get the parent item path
    var parentItemPath = itemPath.substring(0, itemPath.lastIndexOf("/"));

    // Expand the parent item if it is not expanded
    if (!tree.isExpanded(parentItemPath)) {
      tree.expandToLevel(parentItemPath, 1);
    }

    // Select all child items under the parent item
    var parentItem = tree.getItemByPath(parentItemPath);
    var childItems = parentItem.getNodes();
    childItems.forEach(function(childItem) {
      tree.setSelectedItem(childItem, true);
    });
  });
}

// Assuming you have bound the selectionChange event to the onSelectionChange function
tree.attachSelectionChange(onSelectionChange);
```

In the above example, we first obtain the selected items from the `selectionChange` event. Then, for each selected item, we find its parent item by manipulating the item's path. After that, we check if the parent item is expanded or not. If not expanded, we expand it to make child items visible. Finally, we select all the child items under the parent item.

Please note that the code assumes you have already defined the `onSelectionChange` function and attached it to the `selectionChange` event of the sap.m.Tree control. Additionally, make sure to adapt the code to your specific use case and adjust the control ID accordingly.

