This error occurs because the compiler is warning you that you are trying to pass a non-trivial type (`std::string`) through a variadic function, which may lead to undefined behavior at runtime. Variadic functions in C/C++ are designed to work with Plain Old Data (POD) types, which do not have constructors or destructors.

To fix this error, you can either change the function signature to accept `const char*` instead of `std::string`, or you can rewrite the function to handle `std::string` objects properly. Here is an example of how you can modify the function to accept `const char*`:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <cstdarg>

void printStrings(const char* format, ...) {
    va_list args;
    va_start(args, format);

    while (*format != '\0') {
        if (*format == '%') {
            if (*(format + 1) == 's') {
                std::string str = va_arg(args, const char*);
                std::cout << str;
            }
            format += 2;
        } else {
            std::cout << *format++;
        }
    }

    va_end(args);
}

int main() {
    printStrings("Hello, %s!\n", "world");

    return 0;
}
```

Alternatively, if you want to keep using `std::string`, you can modify the function to accept a `std::initializer_list<std::string>` instead of a variadic argument list. Here is an example of how you can do that:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <initializer_list>

void printStrings(std::initializer_list<std::string> strings) {
    for (const std::string& str : strings) {
        std::cout << str;
    }
}

int main() {
    printStrings({"Hello, ", "world!"});

    return 0;
}
```

By making these modifications, you can avoid the error caused by passing a non-trivial type through a variadic function.

