Using the Pointer to Implementation (Pimpl) idiom in combination with the Singleton pattern involves managing the internal implementation details of a class through a pointer to a hidden implementation class. This allows for better encapsulation and separation of interface and implementation. 
Here is an example of how you can implement a Singleton class that uses the Pimpl idiom:

Header file (PxGansRmg.hpp):
```cpp
#pragma once

#include <iostream>
#include <memory>

namespace pxGANs {
    class RmgImpl; // Forward declaration of the implementation class

    class Rmg {
    public:
        static Rmg& getInstance();

        void performAction(); // Example method that uses the implementation

    private:
        Rmg(); // Private constructor
        ~Rmg(); // Private destructor

        Rmg(const Rmg&) = delete;
        Rmg& operator=(const Rmg&) = delete;

        std::unique_ptr<RmgImpl> m_impl; // Pimpl using unique_ptr
    };
}
```

Implementation file (PxGansRmg.cpp):
```cpp
#include "PxGansRmg.hpp"

namespace pxGANs {
    class RmgImpl {
    public:
        void performActionImpl() {
            std::cout << "Performing action...\n";
        }
    };

    Rmg& Rmg::getInstance() {
        static Rmg instance;
        return instance;
    }

    Rmg::Rmg() : m_impl(std::make_unique<RmgImpl>()) {}
    Rmg::~Rmg() = default;

    void Rmg::performAction() {
        m_impl->performActionImpl();
    }
}
```

In this implementation:
- The public `Rmg` class contains a private member `m_impl` that is a pointer to the hidden implementation class `RmgImpl`.
- The class `RmgImpl` contains the actual implementation details and is defined in the implementation file.
- The `performAction()` method in the `Rmg` class delegates the action to the implementation through the Pimpl pointer.

This setup allows you to keep the implementation details hidden from users of the `Rmg` class and effectively combine the Singleton pattern with the Pimpl idiom for improved encapsulation and maintainability. 
You can now instantiate `Rmg` objects and call methods on the singleton instance.
